AB  - The effects of livestock grazing on terrestrial grasslands have garnered a lot of attention; however, little is known about the effects of grazing on multiple ecosystem functions (EFs) and ecosystem multifunctionality (EMF) in coastal saltmarshes.To comprehensively evaluate the ecological effects of grazing and tidal flooding on the saltmarsh, we conducted a grazing-exclusion experiment in the high and middle marsh zones of the Yangtze River Estuary, China.In general, grazing enhanced EMF in saltmarsh, suggesting the potential of rational grazing as an efficient land management practice in estuaries. Although plant biomass, aboveground N of plants, soil organic C, and deposition rate decreased under grazing, activities of soil microbes and nematodes, soil N pool, N mineralization, decomposition and soil respiration increased. The magnitude and mechanisms of grazing effects on EMF differed between high and middle marshes which have different tidal regimes. Grazing had greater impact on the EMF in the middle marsh probably via effects on soil biota and soil conditions, than in the high marshes where alternations of plants played the main role in affecting EMF. We suggest that tidal flooding and associated replenishment of sediments may mitigate the negative effects of grazing on plants and sedimentation and strengthen positive grazing impacts on nutrient cycling and buildup of nutrient pools, thus reinforcing the beneficial effects of grazing on EMF. Our results provide an integrated framework of ecosystem-level responses to livestock grazing in the saltmarsh and highlight the regulatory role of external environmental factors such as tidal flooding. Copyright: CC0 1.0 Universal (CC0 1.0) Public Domain Dedication
