AB  - Humus-rich saltmarsh soils near the Sehestedter Aubetaendeichsmoor at the German North Sea coast are considered to be a source for methane. To get more information on the extent of methanogenesis and its influencing factors in the seasonal course we investigated the methane dynamics in long-term experiments. The methane concentrations were mostly 0-2 mumol g(-1) in the topsoil and 0->10 mumol g(-1) in the subsoil, thus showing increasing values and increasing variability with increasing soil depths. With significant positive correlations to the methane concentrations the methane production rates were often in the range of 100-200 mmol g(-1) d(-1). The sulfate concentrations were 0->10 mM in the topsoil and mostly 0-2 mM in the subsoil, showing an inverse behaviour as compared to the methane dynamics, expressed by the highly negative correlation coefficient and indicating that competitive substrates are the predominant cause for the intense methanogenesis. Allochthonous organic matter is the cause for the natural or geological eutrophy of this site. The SO42-/Cl- ratios ranged from 0.01 -0.11 in the topsoil and from 0-0.03 in the subsoil, showing that sulfate reduction prevails over sulfate oxidation with increasing soil depths. The temporal variability of the methane dynamics indicated that besides substrates the redox potential is an important factor controlling methanogenesis. Methane emission rates were highly variable with up to 120 mg m(-2) d(-1) in the areas with vegetation and even up to 7751 mg m(-2) d(-1) in those without vegetation, clearly revealing the soils to be a source for methane.
